Mutable versus immutable — the property that explains aliasing.

Every python type is either mutable, can be changed in place after creation, or immutable, cannot be changed after creation.

Immutable. Int, float, bool, string, bytes, tuple, frozenset, none. Mutable. List, dict, set, bytearray, most user-defined classes.

This property explains every aliasing surprise. Two names pointing at the same immutable object can never go out of sync — neither can change it. Two names pointing at the same mutable object can, and you have to know they share state.

In code, picture x equals hello, y equals x. Y equals y dot upper creates a new string and rebinds y. X is still hello, unchanged. Then x-s equals a list of one, two, three. Y-s equals x-s. Y-s dot append of ninety-nine mutates the shared list. X-s now shows one, two, three, ninety-nine — surprise.

To get an independent copy, use dot copy or square-bracket-colon-square-bracket. Y-s equals x-s dot copy. Append ninety-nine to y-s. X-s is unchanged. For deeply nested structures, the standard library has copy dot deep-copy. Import copy. Bind nested to a list of two inner lists. Shallow equals nested dot copy. Deep equals copy dot deep-copy of nested. Append ninety-nine to shallow's inner list — that mutates the inner list, which is shared with nested. So nested now shows the mutation. Deep is truly independent.
